SIMPLE: enchant
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Enchant
<hw>En*chant"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Enchanted</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Enchanting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F. <ets>enchanter</ets>, L.
<ets>incantare</ets> to chant or utter a magic formula over or against
one, to bewitch; <ets>in</ets> in, against + <ets>cantare</ets> to sing.
See <er>Chant</er>, and cf. <er>Incantation</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To charm by sorcery; to act on by enchantment; to get control of by
magical words and rites.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And now about the caldron sing,⟦br⟧
Like elves and fairies in a ring,⟦br⟧
<qex>Enchanting</qex> all that you put in.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He is <qex>enchanted</qex>, cannot speak.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To delight in a high degree; to charm; to enrapture;
<as>as, music <ex>enchants</ex> the ear</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Arcadia was the charmed circle where all his spirits forever
should be <qex>enchanted</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Sir P.
Sidney.</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To charm; bewitch; fascinate. Cf.
<er>Charm</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Enchanted</ent>⟦br⟧
